text: Pros:  1. Charles appears to be more mature and understanding. 2. Apocalypse looks pretty cool. 3. Havoc is back.  4. Magneto lifting Charles was a badass scene. 5. Quicksilver is back. (I hope he's confirmed as Erik's son)  6. Erik trying to live a normal life is going to be an interesting turn for his character. 7. When Charles said: "It was just a dream" I really thought that was Patrick Stewart's voice.   Cons:  1. The young versions of Jean, Nightcrawler, and Storm are miscast. Especially Jean. Sophie Turner? Really? Scott's okay though. 2. The graphics look bad (but that's understandable since this is just the first trailer and it'll be better in the movie) 3. Same old "We must unite to stop the end of the world cliche" 4. I hope there's a reason Mystique isn't in her natural form. There isn't a single shot of her blue (except maybe 1:42) 5. Look at 1:39 paused, the shot of the X-Men in the plane. Is it just me or does Sophie Turner look out of place? She doesn't belong there. Like Cyclops and Beast look cool, Quicksilver is chilling in his seat, Moira and Raven are looking at something, and then there's Sophie Turner as Jean just looking like she doesn't belong there. (Did you hear her accent in the beginning? Who bought that?)

text: To everybody having trouble with the TIMELINE, here are my two cents on it.Movies in order: X Men(2000), X2(2003), X3(2006), Origins(2009), First Class(2011), Wolverine(2013), DoFP(2014), Apocalypse(2016).-So timeline in the movies¬†goes something like this: First Class, Days of Future Past¬†(Where Wolverine gets sent back (1973)), --------NOW EVERYTHING AFTER HERE¬†IS BEING REWRITEN AFTER THE¬†TIME ALTERATION IN DOFP (so basically¬†does not happen in current XMEN universe)--------¬†Origins (Wolverine's past before losing memory), X Men, X2, X3, The Wolverine, Days of Future Past¬†(Post-Apocalyptic Future 2025'ish)Now to further¬†explain where Apocalypse (1983)¬†takes place above, its after DoFP (1973).¬†So Wolverine gets sent back in time to stop Raven from becoming the assassin we grew to love in X Men, X2, X3. So since Mystique doesn't become the vicious mutant, X Men, X2, X3, The Wolverine, DoFP (Post Apocalyptic Future) do not happen in the movie universe. The future is being rewritten so to speak. Time was altered¬†so nothing that happened in the movies after First Class¬†will ever take place. Its so confusing but to me it was such a creative way to sort of remake the whole X Men universe, instead of just saying OK lets start from scratch, well they did but in an awesome way. So the young cast in Apocalypse: Jean (Sophie Tuner), Cyclops (Ty Sheridan), Storm (Alexandra Shipp), Beast (Nicholas Hoult), Professor X (James McAvoy), grow old to become the X Men we see at the very end of Days of Future Past: Jean (Famke Janssen), Cyclops (James Marsden), Storm (Halle Berry), Beast (Kelsey Grammer), Professor (Patrick Stewart), so since we saw them in the future its safe to assume that they wont, or shouldn't anyway,¬†be killed off in Apocalypse or future sequels up to that point, .New timeline: First Class, Days of Future Past, Apocalypse, future sequels with new storylines,¬†future at the end of DoFP.¬†So excited!!!

text: I'm excited to see that Apocalypse's look has changed a great deal from the original shoots. Some people still have a problem with it, but I can accept the Egyptian style Apocalypse. For those of you wondering why Apoc has the British type accent instead of an Egyptian one, we must keep in mind that the character has never had an Egyptian accent, throughout the history of his spoken dialogue. This includes the cartoon series, Marvel Vs. Capcom/ X-Men Vs. Street Fighter and X Men Legends 2: Age Of Apocalypse. Voice is still a bit too angelic for me, but I can deal with it. My real problem with the film is the overwhelming amount of dialogue. While dialogue can add a bit to the story, I'm still wondering if there will still be good old fight scenes. Sure, he destroys a lot of things, but how does he stand up against the X-Men? Let's see some more fighting.

text: Apocalypse is rather lackluster in presence here. The trailer here is trying to create the image of a living god, but it was carried out so much better in both X-Men animated series. I mean, at least get his voice right! It'll likely be an entertaining film, but I can't say that I'm eager to see it knowing this Apocalypse has likely been nerfed to where the X-Men will likely defeat him by a typical movie trope of "if we work together we can beat him!".  No. Apocalypse can wipe the floor with the entire X-Men team. There's a reason the Infinity Wars is split into two parts, and why it took the power of an infinity stone to beat Ronan the Accuser, and why X-Men should go to Disney - they respect the source material, even if it makes certain characters nearly immortal.  Seeing how other comic book films are doing so well, X-Men exists in a very weird universe where Wolverine can defeat the Phoenix and travel through time, and Magneto can lift an entire stadium with relative ease, but Apocalypse is somehow terrifyingly powerful. It makes as much sense as power levels in DBZ, and it all comes from a lack of respect for the source material.

text: I liked a lot of the visual Apocalypse's concept. They were based in the power and in the main Apocalypse's characteristics, what makes him different from the others. I have seen many comparisons between Apocalypse and Thanos' version from Marvel's films. To me, Thanos looks like a video game character, even using an actor to capture movements etc. That's the problem when they try to adapt characters from HQs to movies. It's really hard to transpose all the complexity from a character to a CGI "body". I know that when it comes to technology, possibilities are endless, however, It's not enough to replace what a real actor can show using their acting skills . I'm not saying that all CGI characters who have been made in the last years are bad. I'll just always prefer when I see what the actor have prepared as an actor to the character and Oscar Isaac seems to have done a great job. At least it's what I've seen.

In addition Days of Future past was about as seamlessly perfect as one can make an X-Men film and this looks at that level. text: I'm a deaf man now. But, I wasn't always deaf you see! I have a horrible disease called Minere's disease and Usher Type 3 Syndrome. This destroys a persons hearing through out a persons early life until they no longer can hear in their young adult life... It's a horrible and devastating feeling knowing that you'll go deaf but I've accepted my fate and I'm OK being deaf now! I've watched all the X-MEN movies in my life and I've read all the comics too! I've always wanted to be an X-MEN because they are so awesome with their powers!! When this movie is released, I am going to go to the movie theater and I am going to watch this movie with my chin up and watch it like I can still actually hear!  This may only be a movie but this gives me so much hope that maybe one day, I would somehow get some magical power and I would be able to hear again. I would use my power for good. I wasn't always a good person either but since I have went deaf, I've become a better person!  Please, if you have a disability, please know that you are not alone. Don't ever let anyone tell you otherwise because if they do, then they are not worth it to be in your lifes!  Always smile. Always look up and never ever forget who you are..  -Abalam M. Anderson

text: I think a lot of people in this comment thread need to realize that being faithful to the source material, especially for a comic book movie, does not necessarily a good movie make.  I never really read the comics or watched the animated show, so coming from that perspective, I don't see why Apocalypse wouldn't be a good villain from what I see in the trailer here. Just watched a clip from the animated series for comparison, and yeah, his voice isn't modulated and deep, but why the hell does it need to be? If he's presented correctly, there are plenty of ways to make a villain imposing than give him a super deep voice and 7+ feet tall. There's plenty of garbage that does it that way, too, you know. Because it's easy.

text: To everyone who keeps asking about Wolverine:        Keep in mind that Hugh Jackman has been playing that role for 15 years now. Wolverine is supposed to age very slowly, but Hugh isn't looking like a young man any more. This movie takes place in the "early years" of the X-Men; however, they can't just cast a young actor as a "kid Wolverine" like they can for the rest of the characters because, again, he's supposed to have already been a grown adult for several decades (the whole healing factor thing keeping him from aging).  So, really, it's going to get hard for them to keep putting him in if he isn't playing "old man Logan." Unless everyone chooses to ignore the original trilogy that started in 2000 and re-cast, or they start doing some CGI youth-restoration to his face.  Hugh Jackman has already said he's only doing one more Wolverine movie, then he's done with the character (because he's just getting too old for it).

text: Really people. IT'S A COMIC BOOK MOVIE. Lighten up.  it's suppose to be fun--entertaining. The jOY [at least for the 30 to 40 year MARVEL fans] is seeing the comic book pages we grew up with come to life.  In the 80's MARVEL fans could only dream cause DC was taken by a corporate movie studio with millions to spare in movie making.  Those classic movies can be seen as crude--campy and even silly.  BUT it's just a comic book story.   Plots--Storylines--Themes are always going to be simple and even regurgitated.  Comics were always for kids.  How deep can you go. And in today's world many followers are more adult than child.  BUT that's okay.  The inner child in all of us just wants a good vs. evil adventure story that we enjoy and connect too. Since 2000 til now the mighty Marvel Cash machine many of you speak of, has ruled the Hollywood movie scene.  Like tons of styles--fads--media things that "are in the NOW" let's at least appreciate  [and this is just me being a faithful and ever happy Marvel fan since a boyhood in the late 70's] that 15 years is a good run to be hot and still be relevant enough to wake-up the other sleeping Giant DC.  It's now their turn to use all the wonderful characters they have instead of 15 movies of Batman & Superman.... Good Luck DC! and GO JLA Movie production! until til then........like Stan "the Godfather" Lee says...Excelsior! Make mine Marvel!!!

text: As a big fan of X-men, I will watch this movie. However, I am upset with some decisions they have made which I feel changes the original story too much. First of all, where the hell is Cable? How can there be a story about Apocalypse and not Cable? He is the one who really alerted the X-men to Apocalypse and the dark future. He traveled back in time over this! On a side note, Cable is a freaking badass. Secondly, Apocalypse's Four Horsemen in this movie are frustrating to me. They made Magneto, Storm, and Psylocke horsemen which is not at all what happened. Although I think Psylocke was a horseman at one time. Out of those characters, it is unacceptable that Magneto becomes a horseman and serves as a puppet. He should be stronger than that. They already nerfed his character's powers. He can't do several other things in the movies besides move metal. Thirdly, I agree with other commenters that Mystique is getting way too much importance just because she is played by Jennifer Lawrence. I was already bothered by that in Days of the Future Past, and now this is getting out of hand. Also, what has happened to Wolverine? Although it will be a nice change that other characters have screen time instead of Wolverine stealing the show.

text: Don't go watch this movie! It's just another Hollywood money pit! They pump out these filthy movies twice a year, and you suckers pay big money to be disappointed and its just so stupid. STOP WATCHING THESE MOVIES. Think, when was the last time you saw a good Marvel movie? I mean really good. Good voice acting, good effects, good story plot, good flowing story. And perhaps the hardest thing to find in any crappy Marvel movie: MAKING SENSE. Think back to older movies. Like The Avengers. Black Widow and Hawk Eye are completely useless to any of the other characters. Black Widow, can do anything the other Avengers can also do, Hawk Eye is just a guy with an incredibly unrealistic bow. The OLD Marvel was great! The comics were amazing! Now its only for the money, and it already turned into Transformers. Transformers was something made into movies, so older people than us, could see their favorite comic and TV show, into a movie. Its no different from any type of Marvel movie. If someone is going to make any kinda of movie these days, they need to take a good long look at history, and think: Is this really going to con-inside with the past forms of entertainment? Just my opinion.

text: While I've never been much of a fan of the Xmen movies...I did enjoy a few of them, but this looks like it's going to be painfully slow. If the movie is how I imagine it, I think I'll wait for it on DVD..  Act 1: They somehow make sense of the movie taking place in the 80s, spend the first 15 minutes making sure we know what year it is, then they hint to a new super mutant. Being the 1980s, they may tease at the possibility of the colorful suits from the 90s cartoon.  Act 2: We see the gang split again...Magneto allies himself with this new big bad ...and he is likely summoned by a group of "bad" mutants. His four horsemen terrorize the mutant world, and talk about their boss making a NWO. Our heroes chase these 4 around, Magneto becomes one, but will be redeemed..  Act 3: The Xmen rejoin together to in the last 30 minutes find a way to banish the most powerful mutant ever, and we get a "ill be back" kind of tease at the end..  I see act 1-2 being painfully long and drawn out.

text: I feel like all the people commenting on Wolverine and Huge Jackman are part of the reason why the had to reboot the franchise. I'm am not saying that the two are not significant. Hughe Jackman is an amazing actor, and Wolverine is a badass, but it is called X-men, not X-Man. The first three movies were centered so much around one character that the movies suffered for it. Perfect example, in the comics the Phoenix Saga till this day is one of or if not the most expanded upon arcs. But instead of trying to formulate a story that would bring justice to Jean Grey and her complex Character and pretty amazing powers and her relationship with the Phoenix Force, they made her bipolar, and had her killed by mental knifes. A cosmic God which took a Galatic starship to shoot an energy beam at her to kill the Phoenix was killed with three claws. Fox then ook it upon themselves to sell out the comics and make spin offs for Wolverine. Until recently with the back stories from First class and futures past to the new Apocalypse were starting to see the real raw X-men and how they were formed BEFORE Wolverine every became one of them. The only person I feel can never be replaced is Patrick Stewart that bald head was made to be Professor X, anything else is warranted for change and hope they show more accuracy in the depths of each character and their powers.

text: Can I just say I'm sick and tired of hearing people bad-mouth Jennifer Lawrence as Mystique? She was important to the plot of DOFP because it was her actions that resulted in the Sentinel Program getting started, and they had to convince her to stop her plan or else all of mutant-kind was doomed. Now, with Apocalypse threatening to wipe out millions of people and her adopted brother's life (presumably) hanging in the balance, OF COURSE she'd return to help. She was one of the first X-Men in this film universe, so OF COURSE she'd return. Now could you all stop complaining about Lawrence and just move on?

text: Oh.....okay.....I think I'm starting to get what they're doing with Apocalypse in this movie. 0:29-0:39 you see how Apocalypse tenderly lifts Ororo's head up by the chin....like a "loving" father.... there's something so sinister and so creepy about that....  0:55 "You are all my children...and you're lost, because you follow blind leaders...but I am here now....I'm here for you..."  You see what's happening here? They are adding a new dimension to Apocalypse, as someone who is charismatic....actually believable....which IMO will make Apocalypse all the more terrifying....  You can't rely on Apocalypse' voice or his look alone. I think in this movie, they are trying to bring out Apocalypse' inner character, his inner evil, which is a genius move, in my opinion....

text: This is why some might be offended:  Hollywood is deceiving the world of what happens in the end times. The seven year tribulation period or "apocalypse" does not include the returning of God. First the world goes through a fall from faith and the rising of the antichrist claiming to be god.   There are three years and six months of the antichrist's reign then, he will sit in the third temple in Jerusalem and demand worship. At this time, God will unleash his wrath on those that worshiped the antichrist for the other three years and six months. Only at the end of the tribulation does God return to establish his kingdom for the faithful.   Secondly, The antagonist of the film is claiming to be god. Hollywood is literally trying to make God look like a bad guy. God (Yahweh), Jesus (Yeshua) loves all humans and does not want them to sin or worship false gods.

text: Maybe it's just me, but whenever I see huge CGI destruction scenes like with the bridge...I am bored. We, as a modern audience, have seen all this before. I dont feel any connection to movies with over the top CGI action. It was cool when that first came out in the mid 90s, but now I find much more connection to gritty super hero shows, like Netflix "Daredevil" and "Jessica Jones". Make me care about the characters and I will be invested in the show. Dont try and "wow" me with fancy CGI effects. Surely Hollywood is learning this...right?

text: The trailer of the movie X-Men: Apocalypse has made the Hindu leaders furious as the new villain of the movie is comparing himself with the Hindu God Shri Krishna. It‚Äôs not the first time that emotions of Hindus have been hurt by any movie maker and in the past also, some movies have triggered a reaction due to religious sentiments.  The movie buffs got to watch the trailer on Friday in which a blue coloured villain, played by Oscar Isaac, says, ‚ÄúI have been called many things over many lifetimes ‚Äì Ra, Krishna, Yahweh.‚Äù  Rajan Zed, the Hindu Stateman observed the mention and released a statement which says, ‚ÄúSuch trivialisation of Lord Krishna, who is highly revered in Hinduism, is quite inappropriate and disturbing to the devotees‚Äù.  It states further, ‚ÄúLord Krishna was meant to be worshiped in temples or home shrines, not for pushing movies for the mercantile greed of filmmakers. The inappropriate usage of Hindu deities or concepts for commercial or other agenda is not okay. This is another example of the poor use of Hinduism culture in Hollywood. I suggest that Hollywood executives take some form of training in religious and cultural sensitivity so that they have an understanding of the feelings of audiences and communities when creating new products. We would gladly provide the resources.‚Äù

text: For anyone complaining about the continuity, lack of the original X-Men, Wolverine, and the mentions of different Gods from religion I will explain. The whole X-Men timeline was rebooted when Wolverine went back to the past in Days of Future Past. Since the timeline was rebooted this means there will be a whole different chain of events and that's why the movie is set in the past, to see what happened. Second in the past Wolverine is not X-Men yet so that's probably why is not there. His whole Weapon X experiment needs to occur first. Finally the mentioning of those Gods, the whole reason it is there to play up the importance, power, and strength of Apocalypse. Not to cast shade on other religions, so please get over yourself

I am impressed.

text: I'm seeing so many people complain in the comments. PLEASE UNDERSTAND THIS: 1. It is okay that X-Men is not with Marvel right now. They need to FOCUS on properly building the way to Infinity War. What do you prefer; an amazing cinematic universe filled with heroes with an "alternate" universe filled with mutants OR a bunch of characters frantically jammed together?  2. Wolverine is not the center of the X-Men. To those who aren't good in English; MEN is PLURAL. If you did not read the X-Men comics, the mutants shown in the video are the ORIGINAL members. Beast, Jean Grey, Cyclops, Angel, Jubilee (the asian chick who is WOLVERINE'S COUSIN), Storm, Nightcrawler, etc. They are ALL important. They just weren't given the proper screen time in previous films.  3. This movie is the mini"civil war" version of X-Men. Whoever becomes the four horsemen will undoubtedly kick ass.  4. To the religious people of ANY religion complaining about Apocalypse claiming who he says he is; THIS IS JUST FICTION. If you cannot handle that; then do not watch. Simple.

text: The word Apocalypse does not mean the end of the world...It Just means revelation... it is Satan preparing the world for his coming... In the movie God is the villain and Lucifer is the Hero (although we know that Ra, and Krishna are not the other names of the God of the Bible). The Mutants are Satan's angels and the people who have given their lives to him... Well, some of them are God's angels and His people, cause some side with the villain too... Ezekiel 28:18  Talking to Lucifer, God says "Thou hast defiled thy sanctuaries by the multitude of thine iniquities, by the iniquity of thy traffic; therefore will I bring forth a fire from the midst of thee, it shall devour thee, and I will bring thee to ashes upon the earth in the sight of all them that behold thee. Malachi 4 talks about the destruction of the wicked... God desires to make this planet new again, to make it a better place... We see this in the Book of the Apocalypse (Revelation) of Jesus.  But the Second coming posses a threat to Satan and his agencies... Therefore he is summoning his troops for one last battle against God... although he knows he is not going to win...  This Movie is the twisted version of the Great Controversy...

text: To anyone reading this comment who believes in Ra, Krishna, Yahweh (I do),  please do not feel insulted or offended... Not because it's just a movie, but because if you have faith in a religion, you will know not to feel insulted or offended by this sort of thing... If you have faith, you will know that this movie will not make God any lower or make him look evil to other people, whether they believe in God or not...   This is for entertainment, and I believe that movie makers knows that creating a villain that ancient people see as God would sound awesome to the fans... I don't know whether they deliberately add that line to promote something against God... I would like to think that's not the case...   Because movies, right from the beginning, only have one major purpose, for entertainment (and also for making money, that is), not for insulting religion, creating wars in the comments, or making people hate  movies...   So, to those who have faith in the gods mentioned in the trailer, do not feel offended, because they (the movie makers) have no intention of offending or insulting your beliefs (I hope that is the case), just stay strong in your faith....  And to those who do not believe in the gods mentioned in the trailer, if you see people with beliefs commenting about how Fox shouldn't have made those sort of statements regarding beliefs and religion or them being mad about it, understand that they are merely fighting for something they believe in, they are not looking for a fight...  And, finally, I hope we all can enjoy watching this movie, because I have "hope" (#Xavier reference :D).... that this movie will be awesome!

text: So there is a lot of back and forth in the comments about the use of the name of God being applied to Apocalypse. There are those believers (both Hindu and Christian) who are offended and those who do not believe who are offended that the believers are offended. I usually try to stay on topic, but this is an important point, especially in the age we live in today.   For those that do not believe and do not understand the offense taken by those that do, let me put it in non-religious terms. I'm old school. Where I am from, if you do not know someone, you keep their name out of your mouth. If you don't know me, you have no reason to talk about me to others. If you don't know my family, you have no reason to be talking about my family. Stay in your lane and talk about the things in your sphere. To talk about something that does not pertain to you is foolish and a folly.   Same goes for people's religion or beliefs. It's cool that you don't have the same belief. but respect others and keep those names out of your mouth. If you are not Hindu, Christian, Islamic, etc, why do you need to speak the names of their gods.   Respect. But most in this generation don't get that. They run off at the mouth about any and everything because they are nicely hidden away online and don't have to worry about consequences of offending someone. That's cool, but it can't last. Choose to respect others. That really is not a tall order.

text: The premise of this is SO dumb. Why would the world's first mutant be the most powerful? That's not the way evolution works. Evolution takes small, tentative steps, not giant leaps. But over a long period of time, those accumulated small steps gradually produce something significantly different. That's why, for example, the first version of an 'eye' in nature was a rudimentary, crude, light-sensitive mass of cells, not the complex work of art that a human or eagle's eye is. What makes more sense is that the first mutant was someone with powers not extremely different from that of a normal human (e.g. like a Level 1 mutant), and then gradually, evolution began to produce more higher level mutants like Jean Gray, etc., people so different from humans that they might as well be a new species.

text: I finally figured out what's missing in these X-Men films--the street element. If you remember the animated series from the '90s, a great deal of the plots and altercations took place in the urban settings of New York; the street element is also in the comics. When the X-Men faced off against the Morlocks, that was in the underground sewers of the Big City. These films aren't as gritty as their source material...but I do understand Hollywood's need to appeal to wider and more general audience.

text: If you're trying to figure out a timeline involving what Fox has done with X-Men, don't. They had to reboot the series of films within itself by using time travel. That's my best guess as to why they made that film and how it's supposed to make any sense. They have taken my favorite characters from my childhood for 16 yeRs and destroyed them. While this may be a great film as a standalone or beginning with Xmen first class, don't try to watch the first three films or the wolverine films and think it somehow has anything to do with this film. Though I am excited to finally see apocalypse. People want the MCU to eventually tie into the X-Men. This can't happen for several reasons. One of which being that Marvel doesn't even own their own characters, the other being that FOX went to great lengths to destroy the X-Men. If one didn't know better, one might think this was deliberate. They have forever ruined the idea of the X-Men. Try thinking of wolverine and you think of High Jackman....for example. Don't even get me started on The Fantastic Four or their Fantastically terrible reboot. But at least we got Spidey back. And they will actually have a teenager play the 16 year old Peter Parker, not a 35 year old.

text: I really hope Bryan Singer continues to direct X-men movies after this trilogy, Days of Future Past was the best superhero film I've seen since Watchmen, and this only looks better. The apocalypse storyline in the comics and 90's animated series was always one of my favorite parts of the X-men saga. Not to mention the return of some of the cooler characters left out of the reboot so far, like young Nightcrawler, and a young Jean, Scott and so on. If you consider X-men worthless without Wolverine as the main character or because it is "anti-religious" just because it references religion, please GTFO and go watch something more your style. I hope also that Singer gets to direct more superhero franchises other than X-men, maybe he'd even do the marvel trilogy I've most wanted but is not likely, a Maximum Carnage trilogy after the (hopefully final) reboot of Spider-man this time.

text: Well, I'm sold on that soundtrack (assuming it's actually from the movie and not some bought-in reused theme), on the 80s aesthetic and on a few other details (the bald look really does suit McAvoy), and I'm sure Oscar Isaac will make a decent Apocalypse, Ivan Ooze jokes aside.  But the overblown CGI design (blatantly conceived for 3D glasses) and Sophie Turner's dreadful accent and overacting are making it difficult for me to get really excited about this. I'm sure McAvoy and Fassbender will put in another superb performance as they have done in the past two films, but the enthusiasm is simply not there in the same way that it was for First Class and DoFP.

text: The film critics in general praise Days of Future Past and give negative reviews to this movie. The most common criticisms against Apocalypse are that the movie is stuffed with new characters, overloaded with action scenes, and there is a lack of depth for both characters and storyline. If you are expecting a movie which is insightful or educating, there are a lot of movies produced with that purpose.

It will happen to batman and avengers.

text: Although this was the worst of the three prequel X-Men movies, it's still way more entertaining and civilized than any crappy avengers or Disney marvel movie. I love Disney, but I don't live what they're doing to Marvel. The action is also way better and so is the camera work. As a San Francisco Chronicle movie critic said, X-men is more of a "thinking person's [superhero] movie." And the jokes are actually funny, and they weren't trying to make them funny. Avengers tries to hard to be funny and it comes off very awkward and cringe-worthy. I get a headache from rolling my eyes while watching avengers. I can't stand Black Widow, Thor, Iron Man, hulk, and the completely butchered Scarlett Witch and Quicksilver. Captain America is the only superhero they did right, and they made the movie all about the avengers. The only fault of X-Men Apocalypse is that they had too many characters and plot lines, with too little time. But I'd still rather watch it than anything else.

text: You could watch this trailer once and get more entertainment value than the film. You could watch this trailer twice and feel more satisfied than watching the film. You could watch the trailer and the film and wonder, how did this movie go so wrong? You could try to describe the film to someone in your family who hasn't seen it and wonder why scenes that should have been powerful and moving were dull and unaffecting.  The trailer made the movie seem perfect. I was so freaking excited by this trailer, I got so hyped up for this movie, and then the second trailer came out. The second trailer with the digital filter over Issac's voice worried me, no, it angered me if I'm being honest. By the third trailer I was thinking the movie might not be good. By the time I watched the actual movie in theaters I was flipping off the screen with both hands repeatedly, and I didn't even know why until afterwards. I was just so bored that I had to flip the double bird to be entertained, and not even that entertained me, but I kept trying.  I'm still giving the Trailer a thumbs up.

text: This movie does not make sense at all. The timeline is all mixed up. If Charles and Erik were still young that time, that means Jean wasn't born yet. It's because in X-men 3, we see a flashback when Charles and Erik (Old age) was visiting Jean. She was just a kid. If they were young this time, this means that Jean isn't born yet, so as Scott and Storm. All the other characters existed during X-men First Class and the other movies. Even if Jean and the others were already "born," why is there Wolverine in one scene? If Jean and the others saw Wolverine before, why didn't they recognize him in the first X-men movie? Plus, the guy with the wings? We saw him in the 3rd X-men movie. We also saw a flashback where he had his first wings (Which is probably 10 years ago) and later we see him with full grown. This guy also didn't exist because Apocalypse takes place way before. This movie has lots of flaws but the story is good anyways.
